03486nam a22004695i 9780773561229DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19851985xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735612297 a10.1515/97807735612292doi  a(DE-B1597)656924  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR2367.P34 ǂb S56 1985eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a821/.31 aShore, David R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpenser and the Poetics of Pastoral :bA Study of the World of Colin Clout /cDavid R. Shore. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1985] 4c©1985  a1 online resource (202 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Shepheardes Calender: The Moral Eclogues -- tThe Shepheardes Calender; The Pastoral Image -- tSpenser’s Return to Pastoral in Colin Clouts Come Home Againe -- tPastoral and the End of Epic in The Faerie Queene -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Shepheardes Calender (1579) signalled Spenser's desire to assume the role of an English Virgil and at the same time his readiness to leave behind the pastoral world of his apprenticeship and his early persona, Colin Clout. Yet Spenser was twice to return to the pastoral world of Colin Clout, first in Colin Clouts Come Home Againe (written 1591, published 1595), and then again in the sixth and last complete book of The Faerie Queene. In Spenser and the Poetics of Pastoral, David Shore considers the structure of the moral eclogues of the Calender as it defines the pastoral vision that informs and unifies the entire poem. He then examines the themes of poetic idealism and courtly corruption in Colin Clout and sees in their confrontation Spenser's questioning of the public foundations of the poet's heroic endeavour. Finally, he considers Calidore's pastoral retreat in The Faerie Queene and finds in it support for the argument that Spenser's greatest poem is essentially complete. Pastoral is a highly self-conscious genre, especially in Spenser's explorations of the imaginative world of Colin Clout. By bringing together Spenser's three versions of that world, Spenser and the Poetics of Pastoral contributes to a richer appreciation of the pastoral works themselves and to a better understanding of the shape of Spenser's literary career as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClout, Colin (Fictitious character). 0aPastoral poetry, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356122940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561229/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles